Image compression using SVD and Python¶

References:

  • Gilbert Strang, Linear Algebra and Its Applications 4e, section 6.3
  • Tim Baumann, “Image Compression with Singular Value Decomposition”

Public-domain image from the Biodiversity Heritage Library

Singular value decomposition (SVD) factors a matrix into three components:

$$A = U S V^H$$

The middle $S$ is a diagonal matrix containing the square roots of the eigenvalues of $A^H A$ (or $A A^H$). Because $S$ is sorted from greatest $\sigma$ to least, we can zero out the tail end of $S$ as well as the corresponding columns of $U$ and $V$ to produce a lightweight factorization of $A$ that is still quite close.

Since images are matrices, this method is the basis of many widely used image-compression algorithms. Here, I give a practical demonstration of how SVD works and the level of quality one can expect when compressing a typical image.

Make a function that factors the image array using SVD and discards all but a specified portion of the entries. This function outputs three arrays, left,sigma, and right, that correspond to $U$, $S$, and $V^H$. That is, all you have to do is matrix-multiply them together to recover an approximation for the original array.

In [10]:
def svd_prep(img, ratio=1):
    left, diag, right = np.linalg.svd(img)
    # Number of sigma values to keep
    keep = int(np.ceil(diag.size * ratio))
    # Discard unused columns and rows
    diag = diag[:keep]
    left = left[:,:keep]
    right = right[:keep]
    # Superimpose sigma onto a correctly shaped array of zeros
    sigma = np.zeros((keep, keep))
    for i in range(len(diag)):
        sigma[i,i] = diag[i]
    return(left, sigma, right)

Make sure the SVD is working; no compression yet.

In [12]:
a, b, c = svd_prep(img_bw,1)
np.allclose((a @ b @ c),img_bw)

Compress and reconstruct the images. Now compressed_images contains nine different approximations of the original array.

In [17]:
compressed_images = []
for r in ratios:
    a, b, c = svd_prep(img_bw,r)
    # Divide by 255 because we aren't working with ints anymore;
    # matplotlib likes floats between 0 and 1
    b = b / 255
    compressed_images.append(a @ b @ c)

Let’s take a look at the compressed images. Note that substantial detail is preserved at only 13.5% of the filesize.

In [19]:
plt.figure(figsize=(14,14))
plt.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.1,wspace=0.1)
plt.title('Image compression by discarding small sigma-values in SVD')
for i in range(9):
    plt.subplot(3,3,i+1)
    plt.imshow(compressed_images[i],cmap='gray')
    plt.title("SVD compression ratio: {}".format(np.round(ratios[i],decimals=4)))
    plt.axis('off')

Now, let’s see if we can do the same thing while preserving the color. This time, we split the image into three arrays, one corresponding to each channel of the image. We perform SVD on these arrays separately, then recombine.

In [20]:
img_r, img_g, img_b = img[:,:,0], img[:,:,1], img[:,:,2]
In [21]:
compressed_channels=[]
for i in [img_r, img_g, img_b]:
    a, b, c = svd_prep(i,0.1)
    compressed_channels.append(a @ b @ c)

Recombining the channels.

In [24]:
compressed_rgb = np.stack(compressed_channels,axis=2) / 255
compressed_rgb.shape

Let’s compare our compressed image to the original. Matplotlib throws an error because the approximate SVD decomposition has produced negative values in its approximation of $A$; clipping these to 0, which matplotlib does by default, is an acceptable remedy.
